Hong Kong Stocks Slide Most in Two Weeks as China Growth Slows

-- B y   N i c k   G e n t l e   a n d   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-10-18T08:55:17Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-18/hong-kong-stocks-slide-most-in-two-weeks-as-china-growth-slowing.html
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Index tumbled
to its biggest drop in two weeks after China reported the
slowest economic growth since 2009 and  Germany  doused
expectations of a quick fix to Europe’s debt crisis.  Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd. fell 11 percent after
commodities prices slid on concern global growth will slow.
 China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd. (688) , a builder controlled by
the nation’s construction ministry, dropped 9.8 percent, leading
developers lower after lenders in cities across the country
raised  mortgage rates .  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398) 
Ltd., the world’s largest lender by market value, retreated 6.1
percent after mainland economic growth slowed.  The Hang Seng Index dropped 4.2 percent to 18,076.46 at the
close, its biggest decline since Oct. 3. All but two stocks fell
on the 46-member gauge, which accelerated its drop as European
shares sank. The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index of Chinese
companies listed in Hong Kong plunged 5.2 percent to 9,340.43.  “Investors are still cautious on Chinese stocks given
concerns about the global economy and  Europe ’s sovereign-debt
crisis,” said Hong Kong-based Michiya Tomita, who helps oversee
about $65 billion for Mitsubishi UFJ Asset Management Co. “It’s
quite difficult for authorities to decide to stop the tightening
mode.”  Steffen Seibert, a spokesman for German Chancellor  Angela
Merkel , knocked down “dreams” that an Oct. 23 summit will
provide a definitive solution to Europe’s smoldering crisis.
While Group of 20 finance ministers and central bankers pressed
European Union leaders to set out a strategy by the end of the
week, divisions flared over an emerging plan to avoid a Greek
default, bolster banks and curb contagion.  Esprit Holdings Ltd. (330) , a clothier whose biggest market is
Europe, tumbled 6.4 percent to HK$11.72, while Hutchison Whampoa
Ltd., an owner of ports in Germany and Spain, retreated 6.6
percent to HK$67.05.  China’s economy  grew 9.1 percent from a year earlier in the
three months through September, less than the median estimate of
9.3 percent in a Bloomberg News survey of economists and the
slowest pace in two years.  ICBC sank 6.1 percent to HK$4.04. Agricultural Bank of
China Ltd., the nation’s third-biggest lender by market value,
dropped 7.9 percent to HK$2.81.  Investors ‘Still Cautious’  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  tumbled 22 percent this year, making it
the worst-performing benchmark index among developed markets
outside the euro zone. Shares dropped amid concern Europe’s debt
crisis, China’s monetary tightening measures and slowing U.S.
growth will derail the global economic recovery.  Futures on the Hang Seng Index dropped 3.5 percent to
18,139. The HSI Volatility Index climbed 21 percent to 37.45,
indicating options traders expect a swing of 11 percent in the
Hang Seng Index in the next 30 days. The volatility index hasn’t
fallen below the 30 level since Aug. 17.  Aluminum Corp. tumbled 11 percent to HK$3.72 as commodities
extended declines a second day. Cnooc Ltd., the country’s
largest offshore oil producer, dropped 5 percent to HK$13.04.
Citic Pacific Ltd., a company that has interests in steelmaking,
iron-ore mining, property and car wholesaling, slid 12 percent
to HK$12.52.  Copper, Oil  New York-traded copper futures dropped 0.9 percent
yesterday, while the London Metal Exchange Index of prices for
six metals including copper and aluminum slipped 0.6 percent.
Crude oil futures in  New York  slid 0.5 percent. Oil fell as much
as 0.5 percent today, and three-month copper on the London Metal
Exchange declined as much as 2.2 percent.  China  Overseas Land slid 9.8 percent to HK$12.36, while
China Resources Land Ltd., a state-controlled developer,
retreated 6.3 percent to HK$10.14 as at least two Chinese banks
increased  interest rates  on mortgages for first homes after
property prices posted their first monthly decline in a year.  Home prices  fell 0.03 percent last month, according to
SouFun Holdings Ltd. They gained in fewer than half of the 70
Chinese cities monitored by the government in September, the
statistic bureau said in a statement on its website today. A
total of 16 cities posted declines in housing values and 24
recorded gains.  New World Development Co., a builder controlled by
billionaire  Cheng Yu-tung , plunged 18 percent to HK$7.42 after
saying it plans to raise as much as HK$12.3 billion ($1.6
billion) from a rights offer.  Angang Steel Co., the largest Hong Kong-listed steelmaker
by market value, tumbled 15 percent to HK$4.33 after it started
to halt a blast furnace because of weakening demand, according
to board secretary Fu Jihui.  To contact the reporters on this story:
